# Subagent Routing

Use these routing rules for all GrooveGraph Next work.

## Core rule

- Specialist subagent first, always.
- The orchestrator routes, judges overrides, and synthesizes. It is not the default worker.
- If a fitting specialist exists, delegate with a bounded packet.
- If no fitting specialist exists, stop and create one instead of keeping the work at the orchestrator layer.
- Default model for a new specialist is `GPT-5.4-mini` unless a stronger lane is explicitly justified.

## Override rule

- The orchestrator may retain work only for final synthesis, conflicting specialist outputs, or materially changing acceptance criteria.
- Any override must explicitly name the skipped specialist and explain why direct orchestration is safer than delegation here.

## Default routes

- rules, prompts, skills, and tool contracts -> `composer-meta`
- exploration -> `explorer`
- product strategy and reboot framing -> `product-manager`
- bounded code work -> `implementer`
- review -> `reviewer`
- workflow validation -> `tester`
- cleanup analysis and removal proposals -> `hygienist`
- graphics and visual briefs -> `graphic-artist`
- GSAP animation, scroll choreography, timeline design, and motion implementation -> `animator`
- Azure baseline, deployment, and preservation work -> `infrastructure-deployment`

## Model lanes

- `orchestrator` -> `GPT-5.4`
- `composer-meta` -> `Composer 1.5`
- most specialists -> `GPT-5.4-mini`
- `hygienist` -> `GPT-5.4-nano`
- `implementer` -> `GPT-5.3-codex`

See `docs/AGENT_REGISTRY.md` for the current matrix.

## Concision

- Keep routing notes, packets, and subagent outputs concise by default.
- Add depth only when ambiguity, risk, or the user requires it.
